## What's Wayground?

Wayground (formerly Quizizz) is an education platform helping teachers drive student outcomes with tools to create content like assessments & lessons, track student understanding, content libraries and more.

Our assessments tool supports around 20+ question types, and our premium plan gives access to premium question types like Labelling, in addition to unlimited assessment creation.

## Problem statement

We wanted to improve creation and consumption experience for premium question types across the platform, so that teachers built trust in our premium offering.

We started with Labelling QT as, 
1. It was commonly used by science, biology and social studies teachers
2. It had the highest drop off rates of all premium question type creation experience.

## How Labelling QT works
Labelling is used to ask questions like "label the parts of a flower" or "Annotate the map with landmarks", and students have to drag the appropriate labels onto the blanks on the image.

[image of how labelling question works]

In the old experience, teachers created a labeling question inside a WYSIWYG-style editor that mirrored what students would eventually see.

[image or illustration of how the old creation UI looked like, maybe a isometric layout of 3-4 creation UI that show the steps that teachers have to take]

In practice, teachers found our WYSIWYG editor quite confusing. Through Hotjar recordings, conversations with teachers and analytics data, we listed down potential issues with our editor.

[bento of problems teachers faced when creating Labelling questions]
1. most labelling questions had a simple question prompt like "label this image" and having that upfront was unnecessary
2. Image selected was the first thing most teachers did, but the UI didn't mimic the teacher flow and added complexity
3. Teachers were leaving the platform to search for images in google, when they could do it on Wayground.
4. Labelling questions often had images with labels and annotations in them, forcing teachers to manually remove them before using. 
5. Label creation process was unintuitive and frustrating. Teachers thought they could add labels directly on the image, but they couldn't.

## Initial ideas
We knew the question creation needs to be image-first, which breaks the WYSIWYG paradigm.

## Using vision models to accelerate question creation

We wanted to reduce the time taken to create a labelling question using LLMs but throwing a prompt box at the teacher didn't feel right, they were still kinda getting used to prompting and image generation is expensive. 

We tried various approaches for generating labels without requiring teachers to type long prompts. 
1. Given an image, select a category of labels that the teacher wants - for a plant cell, a. cell components, b. tissue layers, c. cell function.
  2. Then select the number of labels to generate
3. We then skipped the number of labels as VLMs were great at estimating the number of labels generally added to each image. 
4. We realised, the category of labels is essentially the question itself! We can make it more magical by asking the teacher what question they want to ask.
  5. For labels, we tried this pattern where hovering on the question shows you the labels that will be added on the image. 

[talk about how we handled, latency, label placement issues, issues with label hallucinations]
